Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Issue in .NET 8 |
|----------|---------|-----------------|
| `Stop()` → `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop + force stop | `PlatformNotSupportedException` / `SYSLIB0006` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Cleanup on abort | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue loop after abort | `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop (replaces ResetAbort + loop re-check)
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait for the thread to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs and `OperationCanceledException` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal; no `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` filter avoids swallowing unrelated exceptions |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | You control the loop — just exit it |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Actually waits for completion instead of hoping |

## Critical Pitfalls

1. **`GetNextItem` must accept the token.** If it blocks (e.g., `queue.Take()`), it will never see cancellation without the token. Use `BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken)` or async equivalents.

2. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` broadly.** The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not one from an unrelated source.

3. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It holds timer/callback resources. The `IDisposable` implementation handles this.

4. **`Thread.Sleep` inside the loop?** Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` — it wakes immediately on cancellation instead of sleeping the full duration.

5. **If `GetNextItem` calls unmodifiable code** that truly blocks with no token support, you cannot cancel it cooperatively. The fallback is to move that work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()`.
